1. Extending the [**Transformer**](https://spark.apache.org/docs/2.3.0/api/java/org/apache/spark/ml/Transformer.html) interface means we can automate DataFrame transformations
2. Given that Machine Learning is all about repeatable results having explicit Transformation Stages allows a phasic based approach to data preparation

%spark
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.{IndexToString, StringIndexer, OneHotEncoderEstimator, VectorAssembler}
import org.apache.spark.ml.Pipeline
import org.apache.spark.ml.PipelineModel
import org.apache.spark.ml.clustering.KMeans
import org.apache.spark.ml.evaluation.ClusteringEvaluator

val netflixCategoryDataWithRatingSchema = "`show_id` BIGINT,`category` STRING, `rating` STRING"
val netflixCategoryStructSchema = StructType.fromDDL(netflixCategoryDataWithRatingSchema)

val contentWithCategories = spark.read
  .format("org.apache.spark.sql.redis")
  .schema(netflixCategoryStructSchema)
  .option("key.column", "show_id")
  .option("table", "netflix_category_rating")
  .load()

contentWithCategories.printSchema

val categoryIndexer = new StringIndexer()
  .setHandleInvalid("keep") // options are keep, skip, error
  .setInputCol("category")
  .setOutputCol("category_index")

val ratingIndexer = new StringIndexer()
  .setHandleInvalid("keep")
  .setInputCol("rating")
  .setOutputCol("rating_index")

val fittedCategoryIndexer = categoryIndexer.fit(contentWithCategories.select("category").distinct())
val fittedRatingIndexer = ratingIndexer.fit(contentWithCategories.select("rating").distinct())

val encoder = new OneHotEncoderEstimator()
  .setInputCols(Array("category_index","rating_index", "rating_class"))
  .setOutputCols(Array("category_vec", "rating_vec", "rating_class_vec"))

val vectorAssembler = new VectorAssembler()
  .setInputCols(Array("category_vec","rating_vec", "rating_class_vec"))
  .setOutputCol("features")

val transformationPipeline = new Pipeline()
    .setStages(
        Array(
            fittedRatingIndexer,
            fittedCategoryIndexer,
            new RatingClassificationTransformer,
            new IsKidSafeTransformer,
            encoder,
            vectorAssembler
        )
    )

val fittedPipeline = transformationPipeline.fit(contentWithCategories)

val pipelineLocation: String = "file:///learn/pipeline/"
fittedPipeline.write.overwrite.save(pipelineLocation)

val transformed = fittedPipeline.transform(contentWithCategories)

transformed.printSchema
transformed.createOrReplaceTempView("logistic_prep")

import org.apache.spark.ml.classification.LogisticRegression

/*
// Use to explore how to tune the LogisticRegression model - per training video
val lr = new LogisticRegression()
  .setMaxIter(10)
  .setLabelCol("label")
  .setRegParam(0.3)
  .setElasticNetParam(0.8)
  .setTol(1E-6)
  .setFitIntercept(true)
*/

// Use as the tuned model if you want to skip tuning exercize
val lr = new LogisticRegression()
  .setMaxIter(10)
  .setLabelCol("label")
  .setRegParam(0.3)
  .setElasticNetParam(0.2)
  .setTol(1E-6)
  .setFitIntercept(false)

val Array(training, test) = transformed.randomSplit(Array(0.8, 0.2), seed = 12345L)


// Fit the model
val lrModel = lr.fit(training)
println(s"Coefficients: ${lrModel.coefficients} Intercept: ${lrModel.intercept}")

val trainingSummary = lrModel.binarySummary

// Obtain the objective per iteration.
val objectiveHistory = trainingSummary.objectiveHistory
println("objectiveHistory:")
objectiveHistory.foreach(loss => println(loss))

// Obtain the receiver-operating characteristic as a dataframe and areaUnderROC.
val roc = trainingSummary.roc
roc.show()
println(s"areaUnderROC: ${trainingSummary.areaUnderROC}")

// Set the model threshold to maximize F-Measure
val fMeasure = trainingSummary.fMeasureByThreshold
val maxFMeasure = fMeasure.select(max("F-Measure")).head().getDouble(0)
val bestThreshold = fMeasure.where($"F-Measure" === maxFMeasure)
  .select("threshold").head().getDouble(0)
lrModel.setThreshold(bestThreshold)

val predicted = lrModel.transform(test.drop("label"))

predicted.createOrReplaceTempView("logistic_test")

## Real Talk: We can predict Kid Safe movies with a perfect score. What about the Real World?
1. In the real world we rarely get picture perfect classifications. If you see the column `probability` you'll see it isn't always >90 but the prediction is just about spot on.
2. Things are so picture perfect because we were able to feed the Model the encoded `rating_class_vec` which hints to the LogisticRegession model during fitting almost exactly what we want. Given that we have the values 0.0, 1.0, 2.0 for kid safe, safe for most, and enjoys anything.
3. As a Follow up exercize. Remove the `rating_class_vec` from the vectorAssembler and rerun the training (lm.fit) to see how removing the extreme hint changes the sensitivity and specificity of the model (eg. how it optimizes for True Positives, False Negatives, True Negatives and False Positives).

import org.apache.spark.ml.evaluation.RegressionEvaluator
import org.apache.spark.ml.regression.LinearRegression
import org.apache.spark.ml.tuning.{ParamGridBuilder, TrainValidationSplit}

// this model uses the same label, features to fit the model as the LogisticRegression
val lr = new LinearRegression()
    .setMaxIter(10)

val paramGrid = new ParamGridBuilder()
  .addGrid(lr.regParam, Array(0.1, 0.01))
  .addGrid(lr.fitIntercept)
  .addGrid(lr.elasticNetParam, Array(0.0, 0.5, 1.0))
  .build()

// In this case the estimator is simply the linear regression.
// A TrainValidationSplit requires an Estimator, a set of Estimator ParamMaps, and an Evaluator.
val trainValidationSplit = new TrainValidationSplit()
  .setEstimator(lr)
  .setEvaluator(new RegressionEvaluator)
  .setEstimatorParamMaps(paramGrid)
  // 80% of the data will be used for training and the remaining 20% for validation.
  .setTrainRatio(0.8)
  // Evaluate up to 2 parameter settings in parallel
  .setParallelism(2)

// Run train validation split, and choose the best set of parameters.
val model = trainValidationSplit.fit(training)

paragraphs.text:
%md
## Conclusion: Batch Mode Spark ML
What we learned.
1. We all now know how to take an unknown dataset (`netflix_titles.csv`) and import (`load`) that into Apache Spark
2. From the loaded data, we have learned how to inspect the underlying `schema` and view the inferered types (`StructType`) of the underlying `DataFrame`
3. We have learned how to view the summary statistics of each column across all rows by calling `describe` on the data
4. We have learned how to use SQL to manipulate the DataFrames through the use of `Views`. `df.createOrReplaceTempView`
5. We have learned how to `read` and `write` to `redis` using the `spark-redis` library. Including how to create `tables`.
6. We have learned how to use `Unsupervised Learning` to cluster the Netflix data into logical clusters. This exercise lead us to use supervised learning techniques.
7. Before we could use our `LogisticRegression` or `LinearRegression` models we had to first `feature engineer` the data. We used `StringIndexer` and `OneHotEncoderEstimator` to generate features
8. We learned how to create a `Transformer` to apply to a Spark ML `Pipeline` so we could create both a `rating_class` as well as a `label` for kidSafe or notKidSafe
9. We then learned how to really rock and roll with the `Pipelines` and were able to create a full transformation pipeline and then split our training and test data
10. Next we applied the transformed DataFrame with `label` and `features` to our LogisticRegression model.
11. And we concluded by learning about how to use `ParamGrid` to automatically test which model hyperparameters are best for our final model
12. We all learned something new.
